---

<ElementLayout
  title="dd"
  description="The definition description element provides the description, definition, or value associated with a term in a definition list."
  elementName="dd"
  category="native"
  nativeGroup="Lists"
  currentPath="/docs/elements/native/dd/"
>
  <section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> element (definition description) provides the description, definition, or value for the preceding <a href="/docs/elements/native/dt/"><code>&lt;dt&gt;</code></a> element(s) in a <a href="/docs/elements/native/dl/"><code>&lt;dl&gt;</code></a> (definition list).</p>
    <p>By default, <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> elements are indented from the left margin to visually distinguish them from their associated terms.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Semantic Meaning</h2>
    <p>A definition description conveys that:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The content is a definition, explanation, or value</li>
      <li>It is associated with one or more preceding terms (<code>&lt;dt&gt;</code>)</li>
      <li>It represents the "value" part of a name-value pair</li>
      <li>Multiple descriptions can be associated with the same term</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Screen readers announce the relationship between descriptions and their terms, helping users understand the data structure.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Definitions for glossary terms</li>
      <li>Values in metadata displays</li>
      <li>Answers in FAQ sections</li>
      <li>Values in key-value pairs</li>
      <li>Product attribute values</li>
      <li>Any description associated with a term</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>When Not to Use</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Outside of a <code>&lt;dl&gt;</code> element</li>
      <li>Without a preceding <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> element</li>
      <li>For regular list content - use <a href="/docs/elements/native/li/"><code>&lt;li&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For standalone paragraphs - use <code>&lt;p&gt;</code></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Basic Usage</h2>

    <div class="example">
      <dl>
        <dt>Accessibility</dt>
        <dd>The practice of making websites usable by as many people as possible, including those with disabilities.</dd>

        <dt>Responsive Design</dt>
        <dd>An approach to web design that makes web pages render well on a variety of devices and window or screen sizes.</dd>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Basic definition list">{basicListCode}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Multiple Descriptions</h2>
    <p>A term can have multiple <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> elements, each providing a different definition, meaning, or aspect.</p>

    <div class="example">
      <dl>
        <dt>Port</dt>
        <dd>A harbor or haven for ships.</dd>
        <dd>A virtual point where network connections start and end.</dd>
        <dd>A type of fortified wine from Portugal.</dd>
        <dd>To transfer software from one system or environment to another.</dd>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Multiple descriptions for one term">{multipleDescriptionsCode}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Shared Description</h2>
    <p>Multiple terms can share the same <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> description. This is useful for synonyms or alternate names.</p>

    <div class="example">
      <dl>
        <dt>RGB</dt>
        <dt>Red Green Blue</dt>
        <dd>A color model in which red, green, and blue light are combined to reproduce a wide array of colors.</dd>

        <dt>CMYK</dt>
        <dt>Cyan Magenta Yellow Key</dt>
        <dd>A subtractive color model used in color printing, referring to the four ink plates used.</dd>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Multiple terms sharing a description">{sharedDescriptionCode}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Rich Content</h2>
    <p>Definition descriptions can contain any flow content, including paragraphs, lists, links, and more.</p>

    <h3>With Paragraphs</h3>
    <div class="example">
      <dl>
        <dt>Progressive Enhancement</dt>
        <dd>
          <p>A strategy for web design that emphasizes core webpage content first.</p>
          <p>Additional functionality and styling are layered on top for browsers that support them.</p>
        </dd>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <h3>With Lists</h3>
    <div class="example">
      <dl>
        <dt>Key Features</dt>
        <dd>
          <ul>
            <li>Lightweight and fast</li>
            <li>No dependencies</li>
            <li>Fully accessible</li>
            <li>Mobile-first design</li>
          </ul>
        </dd>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Description with nested list">{nestedListCode}</code-block>

    <h3>With Links and Code</h3>
    <div class="example">
      <dl>
        <dt>Documentation</dt>
        <dd>
          See the <a href="#">official documentation</a> for more details.
          Use <code>npm install</code> to get started.
        </dd>
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>As Metadata Values</h2>
    <p>Definition descriptions work well as values in metadata displays.</p>

    <div class="example">
      <dl>
        <dt>Status</dt>
        <dd><span style="color: green;">Active</span></dd>

        <dt>Last Updated</dt>
        <dd><time datetime="2024-01-15">January 15, 2024</time></dd>

        <dt>Contributors</dt>
        <dd>
          <a href="#">Alice</a>,
          <a href="#">Bob</a>,
          <a href="#">Carol</a>
        </dd>

        <dt>Downloads</dt>
        <dd><data value="50000">50,000</data></dd>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Definition list as metadata display">{metadataCode}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>FAQ Pattern</h2>
    <p>Definition lists are excellent for FAQ sections where questions are terms and answers are descriptions.</p>

    <div class="example">
      <dl>
        <dt>What is Vanilla Breeze?</dt>
        <dd>Vanilla Breeze is a layered HTML component system that uses native elements as a foundation, enhanced with CSS custom properties and optional JavaScript for interactive components.</dd>

        <dt>Do I need JavaScript to use it?</dt>
        <dd>No. The core styling works with pure HTML and CSS. JavaScript is only required for interactive components like accordions and dialogs.</dd>

        <dt>Is it accessible?</dt>
        <dd>Yes. Vanilla Breeze follows WCAG 2.1 AA guidelines and uses semantic HTML with appropriate ARIA attributes where needed.</dd>
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>

    <h3>Screen Reader Behavior</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Announced as the description or definition for preceding terms</li>
      <li>Associated with <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> elements in the list context</li>
      <li>Multiple descriptions announced sequentially</li>
      <li>Rich content within descriptions is fully accessible</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Best Practices</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Write clear, meaningful descriptions</li>
      <li>Use appropriate semantic elements within descriptions</li>
      <li>Ensure every <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> is associated with at least one <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code></li>
      <li>Keep descriptions focused and relevant to their terms</li>
      <li>Use lists or paragraphs within <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> for complex content</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CSS Properties</h2>

    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Property</th>
          <th>Value</th>
          <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>margin-inline-start</code></td>
          <td><code>var(--size-l)</code></td>
          <td>Left indentation to distinguish from terms</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>When a <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> is followed by a <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> (starting a new term group), the <code>dd + dt</code> selector adds <code>margin-block-start: var(--size-m)</code> to create visual separation between groups.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Content Model</h2>

    <h3>Permitted Content</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Flow content (paragraphs, lists, figures, etc.)</li>
      <li>Inline elements (links, code, emphasis, etc.)</li>
      <li>Text content</li>
      <li>Nested definition lists</li>
      <li>Any valid HTML that makes sense in context</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Required Parent</h3>
    <p>Must be a child of <code>&lt;dl&gt;</code>, optionally wrapped in a <code>&lt;div&gt;</code>.</p>

    <h3>Required Siblings</h3>
    <p>Must be preceded by one or more <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> elements (or another <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> that shares the same <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code>).</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Common Patterns</h2>

    <h3>Simple Key-Value</h3>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Simple key-value pattern">{simpleKeyValueCode}</code-block>

    <h3>Term with Multiple Definitions</h3>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Term with multiple definitions">{termMultipleDefinitionsCode}</code-block>

    <h3>Multiple Terms, Single Definition</h3>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Multiple terms sharing definition">{multipleTermsSingleDefinitionCode}</code-block>

    <h3>Rich Description Content</h3>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Rich content in description">{richDescriptionCode}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Related Elements</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/dl/"><code>&lt;dl&gt;</code></a> - Definition list container (required parent)</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/dt/"><code>&lt;dt&gt;</code></a> - Definition term (required sibling)</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/custom-elements/dl-item/"><code>&lt;dl-item&gt;</code></a> - Custom element for grouping dt/dd pairs</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/ul/"><code>&lt;ul&gt;</code></a> - Can be nested inside <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> for detailed lists</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/ol/"><code>&lt;ol&gt;</code></a> - Can be nested inside <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> for sequential details</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Patterns Using This Element</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> element is used in these patterns:</p>
    <layout-grid data-layout-min="200px" data-layout-gap="m">
      <a href="/docs/patterns/data/description-list/" class="section-card">
        <h3>Key-Value / Description List</h3>
        <p>Display key-value pairs in horizontal or stacked layouts</p>
      </a>
    </layout-grid>
  </section>
</ElementLayout>
